&nbsp;
The United States will ask Ukraine to make territorial concessions, > a hypothesis to which Kiev has already said available, intended to use as a commodity of exchange the zones still under its control in the Russian region of Kursk>. Moscow aspires to the recognition of the regions of Crimea, Donetsk, Lugansk, Kherson and Zaporizhzhia, > but of the latter two does not even control their respective leaders. Ukrainian troops will probably have to leave the Russian Kursk region, while Russian troops will have to leave the Ukrainian Kharkiv region.
&nbsp;
The question of security guarantees of Ukraine is particularly difficult: It is not clear who should provide them, so that they are considered reliable in the current circumstances. Trump has appointed American negotiating team leaders to resolve these and other issues: Secretary of State Marco Rubio, > Director of Cia John Ratcliffe>, National Security Counsellor Michael Waltz > and Special Envoy for the Middle East Steve Witkoff; > the latter, on the eve of Trump's call to Putin, on February 11 he went to Moscow to take the teacher Mark Vogel, released from a Russian prison in exchange for the release of the co-founder of cryptocurrency BTC-e, Alexander Vinnik.
&nbsp;
According to the American press, in Moscow Whitkoff would meet some representatives of the Russian authorities, perhaps even Putin himself. Among the Russian officials, it is believed to have seen Kirill Dmitriev, for a long time the Council of the Russian Fund for direct investment. Dmitriev played an informal link between Russian authorities and Trump administration during his first term.
&nbsp;
Andriy Yermak reported that Zelensky has already ordered the formation of a negotiating group. It is expected that joint work with the American side will begin at the Munich Security Conference on the weekend.&nbsp;

