AGI - Looking at the cinema as a mirror in which the profound changes that three years of war are producing in Russia and Ukraine is a natural exercise to Alexander Rodnyansky>. Famous film producer, originally from Kiev, built his career in Moscow, conquering several international awards, but also the rage of the authorities. "In Russia now prevails fantasy, in Ukraine instead it is the opposite and you make many documentaries, works related to the close topicality; not by chance, the first Ukrainian film to win an Oscar was last year the documentary 'Mariupol'', says Rodnyansky in an interview with AGI a few weeks from the third anniversary of the invasion and after the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2025-02-12/telefonata-trump-putin-negozia The lens of the cinema is also used in his book, released at the end of 2024: 'Loveless. Putin's Russia in nine films >' (published in Russian by Meduza).
&nbsp;
In the volume he traces his career and analyzes Russia's political and cultural life from 2000 to today to find an answer to the question that torments the world from 24 February 2022: how could it happen? "In Russia, all themes related to the real situation in the country are in fact banned," he says on the phone while he is in Egypt on the set, "you can't make movies about the fact that there is a war and that it doesn't like everyone, you can't talk about the challenges and social and economic problems." In general the Russian cinema of today refutes reality: "There are comedies or films based on national mythology. The public does not want to see on the screen the world in which he lives every day". The situation in Ukraine is the opposite: "In Moscow restaurants open and people enjoy themselves. In Kiev there are bombings, people who go to war, return invalid. In Russia there is also money for cinema, while in Ukraine films can only be made with the help of foreign partners."
&nbsp;
Rodnyansky, 63 years old, is one of the most influential figures of contemporary Russian cinema, member of the American Film Academy, four-time Oscar candidate and winner of the Cannes Film Festival, produced films and TV series also with public funding and well knows President Volodymyr Zelensky > as his advisor Andrii Yermark>. Until 2022, he worked in Russia, but as soon as the invasion began, on February 24, 2022, his social posts, always critical of the war, were not unnoticed. "The then Minister of Defense ordered the Minister of Culture to ban all my work in Russia, I knew that my position against war would inevitably be punished." The Ukrainian producer is very followed on Instagram where he regularly publishes his views on the conflict and actively discusses it with his nearly 700,000 followers.
&nbsp;
In October last, a Moscow court sentenced him to eight and a half years in prison for "fake news spread" > on the army. Rodnyansky - who says he does not recognize the authority of Russian Justice - is convinced that the judges' decision "is intended to instill more fear in the Russian film community and prevent it from publicly criticising the unjust war in Ukraine and Vladimir Putin. Tens of the best Russian writers and musicians have been condemned for this before me: because they want to silence the voices against war." After sodalizi with some of the most famous contemporary Russian directors - including Andrey Zvjagintsev, Fyodor Bondarchuk and Kantemir Balagov> - and having worked moving in that gray area where before the war the Kremlin allowed artists to swing on the border between propaganda and denunciation, Rodnyansky wrote a book with the aim of telling Russia of the Putin era in nine films and
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
"The chapter on the film 'The ninth company' >(Bondarchuk, 2005), tells of the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan, the defeat in the Cold War, the collapse of the USSR, an event that in Ukraine was perceived as a liberation, but that in Russia was a real trauma," Rodnyansky said. "The chapter on 'Stalingrad' >(Bondarchuk, 2013) focuses on the cult of victory in the Second World War, which became angular stone of Putin's ideology," explains the producer, pointing out that "unlike the Soviet directors, who had fought in the first person and therefore believed war unacceptable, the new directors are militarists".
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
"The war has been normalized, it is seen as a legitimate continuation of politics, a social lift for young people and a tool for achieving national interests." But for Rodnyansky, the films that best describe the life in Russia of the last 20 years, are those of the Siberian director Zvyagintsev > (already Golden Lion in Venice and winner of a Golden Globe): "His 'Elena'> (2011) tells the model on which Russian society is built in the first 10 years of Putin's power; 'Leviathan' >(2014), instead, represents the union of temporal and spiritual power in a single organism that takes total control over the society and private life of the individual and then 'Loveless'> (2017), which gives the title to the book, focuses on the lack of empathy in Russian society, the inability to help the neighbor and the lack of tools of civil society that allow to correct the political system".
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
"Russia is a country that fails to get rid of its secular diseases and the tragedy of its imperial history. We are illusive, first of all, that the country could have a development in a European and democratic sense, which would become not like Italy, but perhaps similar to Poland", admits the producer. "Russia, on the other hand, returned to what remained of the USSR and the Empire: hypocrisy, repression, aggressive wars." For this transformation, he regretted, "it was necessary to destroy some of the key institutions of the Soviet past and their heirs: the imperialist mentality has not changed, the economy has developed on corruption, social difference, delation, deceit." The control over cultural production has always been important for a regime, but it has become even more after the anti-government protests of Piazza Bolotnaya (2011-2012) > in Moscow, animated by the young people of the middle class, the creatives and the free professionals, whose loyalty Putin thought he had bought with the well-being and economic growth he had conquered in his first two mandates.
&nbsp;
"From that moment, the Kremlin strongly took control over this sphere of society," recalls Rodnyansky, "start a vine tour of the NGOs that helped different initiatives from below, closed independent media, put under investigation and imprisoned representatives of civil society and opposition leader creating a complex system of control made by a part of actions to instill fear and by the other of initiatives to buy the loyalty of subsidiary segments and similar wages of the increase. The mix of these factors has made Russian society frightened and silent > although many intimately do not agree with what is happening." The case of Rodnyansky himself is emblematic: "On the one hand, after the large-scale invasion of Ukraine, the Russian state has tripled its investments in propaganda cinemas and on the other, those who express critical opinions like me get detentive peniles," he says.
&nbsp;
Familiar with the rooms of power, from Ukrainian Rodnyansky still hopes a compromise to end the war. " Donald Trump's arrival at the White House means a lot to negotiate. > The U.S. is the main supporter of Ukraine, without them it would not have managed to counter Russia. Now, an American president who believes it is essential to negotiate is an important condition and it is clear that without compromises from all sides an agreement will not be possible; to say what compromise is difficult. One thing, though, is clear to me: Ukraine will never yield on its independent sovereign state that can decide its future."
